{"title_page": "Elaine McCusker", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Elaine McCusker\n|image       = Elaine A. McCusker official photo.jpg\n|office      = Acting [[Under Secretary of Defense (Comptroller)|United States Under Secretary of Defense (Comptroller)]]\n|president   = [[Donald Trump]]\n|term_start  = July 31, 2019\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[David Norquist]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_date  = \n|birth_place = [[Pekin, Illinois]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|education   = [[Illinois Central College]]<br>[[University of Dallas]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n|awards      = [[Navy Superior Civilian Service Award]] (2008)<br>[[Secretary of Defense Exceptional Civilian Service Award]] (2011)<br>[[Department of Defense Distinguished Civilian Service Award]] (2016)\n}}\n\n'''Elaine A. McCusker''' is an American government official who has held the position of Deputy [[Under Secretary of Defense (Comptroller)]], one of the offices of [[United States Principal Deputy Under Secretary of Defense]], since 2017;<ref name=\"af-bio\">{{cite web | url = https://www.af.mil/About-Us/Biographies/Display/Article/108718/elaine-a-mccusker/ | title = Elaine A. McCusker | work = Biographies | publisher = United States Air Force | date = March 2018 | accessdate = 2019-12-30 }}</ref>  She was nominated by President [[Donald Trump]] to become United States Principal Deputy Under Secretary of Defense in April 2017 and was confirmed on August 1, 2017.<ref>{{cite news release|title=President Announces Picks for Senior Pentagon Posts|url=https://www.defense.gov/News/Article/Article/1120965/president-announces-picks-for-senior-pentagon-posts/|accessdate=May 1, 2017|publisher=United States Department of Defense}}</ref><ref>{{cite news release|title=President Donald J. Trump Announces Intent to Nominate Key Administration Posts|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/16/president-donald-j-trump-announces-intent-nominate-key-administration|accessdate=May 1, 2017|agency=Office of the Press Secretary|publisher=The White House|date=March 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kheel |first1=Rebecca|title=Navy secretary, seven other Pentagon posts confirmed|url=http://thehill.com/policy/defense/344923-navy-secretary-seven-others-confirmed |accessdate=August 4, 2017|publisher=The Hill|date=August 2, 2017}}</ref> In November 2019, the White House announced that McCusker would be nominated to succeed [[David Norquist]] as the [[Under Secretary of Defense (Comptroller)]].<ref>{{cite news release |title=President Donald J. Trump Announces Intent to Nominate Personnel to Key Administration Post |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/president-donald-j-trump-announces-intent-nominate-personnel-key-administration-post-14/ |accessdate=November 8, 2019 |website=The White House |date=November 6, 2019}}</ref> On March 2, 2020 it was reported that her nomination was being withdrawn by the White House following reports that in 2019 she had warned that freezing military aid to Ukraine might not be legal.<ref>{{cite news |title=White House withdraws nomination of Defense official who questioned Ukraine aid freeze |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/02/white-house-defense-official-nomination-118909 |first=Connor |last=O'Brien |date=March 2, 2020 |website=Politico |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>https://nypost.com/2020/03/02/trump-drops-elaine-mccuskers-pentagon-nomination-in-impeachment-fallout/</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMcCusker is from [[Pekin, Illinois]],<ref name=\"sjr-sings\"/> one of the daughters of William and Kathleen Brown McCusker. Her father was chairman of the board of the Illinois Federation for Right to Life.<ref>{{cite news | work = Pekin Daily Times | title = William McCusker | date = August 26, 2009 | url = https://www.pekintimes.com/article/20090826/NEWS/308269949 | accessdate = 2019-12-30 }}</ref> She is a graduate of [[Peoria Notre Dame High School]] and [[Illinois Central College]].<ref name=\"sjr-sings\">{{cite news | work = [[The State Journal-Register]] |edition=web |location=Springfield, Illinois | title = Pekin woman sings praises of latest combat vehicle | first=Kevin |last=Sampier | date = September 30, 2007 | url = https://www.sj-r.com/x428370762 | accessdate = 2019-12-30 }}</ref>  In 1989 she received a Bachelor of Arts in political philosophy from the [[University of Dallas]], Texas.<ref name=\"af-bio\"/>\n\n==Career==\n{{Trump-Ukraine scandal}}\nMcCusker previously worked for the [[United States Energy Department]]'s [[Argonne National Laboratory]], the [[United States Senate Committee on Armed Services]], the Pentagon Comptroller's office, and the Navy Department. At the Navy Department, she was a special assistant for the [[MRAP|Mine-Resistant Ambush Protected]] vehicle program.<ref name=\"sjr-sings\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Freedberg Jr.|first1=Sydney|last2=Clark|first2=Colin|title=Trump Picks Technocrats, Not Billionaires, For Top Pentagon Posts|url=http://breakingdefense.com/2017/03/trump-picks-technocrats-not-billionaires-for-top-pentagon-posts/|accessdate=May 1, 2017 |publisher=Breaking Defense|date=March 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMcCusker contributed to announcements in September 2019 regarding Trump's plan to divert Pentagon funds to [[Trump wall|build a wall along the U.S.-Mexico border]].  McCusker announced wall construction could begin as within three months on federally owned land. Construction of the wall on other government or privately owned land would commence at a later date, she noted.<ref>{{cite news | work = [[The Wall Street Journal]] | title = Trump Administration Advances Plan to Shift $3.6 Billion in Military Funds to Border Wall | date = September 3, 2019 | url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-administration-advances-plan-to-shift-3-6-billion-in-military-funds-to-border-wall-11567551501?mod=searchresults&page=1&pos=1 }}</ref>\n\nMcCusker was identified as one of the federal officials with knowledge of [[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal|President Trump's effort to keep Ukraine from receiving aid authorized by Congress]]. Emails that she sent and received regarding the matter were included in documents obtained by the [[Center for Public Integrity]] in response to a [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] request.<ref>{{cite news | work = Arkansas Democrat Gazette | title = Ukraine aid frozen just after call, files show | date = December 22, 2019 | url = https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2019/dec/22/ukraine-aid-frozen-just-after-call-file/?news-national }}</ref> [[Mike Duffey|Michael Duffey]], a political appointee in White House's [[Office of Management and Budget]] (OMB), emailed McCusker and others an hour and a half after Trump\u2019s call with Ukrainian leader Zelenksy, requesting they \"hold off\" on distributing aid to the Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news | work = Vanity Fair | title = Report: White House Froze Ukraine Aid 91 Minutes After Trump Asked For a \u201cFavor\u201d | date = December 23, 2019 | first = Bess | last = Levin | url = https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/12/white-house-froze-ukraine-aid-91-minutes-after-trump-zelensky-call | accessdate = 2019-12-30 }}</ref>\n\nMcCusker then sent emails to the OMB expressing concern that by witholding funds from the Ukraine, the White House was violating the [[Congressional Budget and Impoundment Control Act of 1974|Impoundment Control Act]], which requires that the executive branch spend appropriations that have been approved by [[United States Congress|Congress]].<ref>{{cite news | work = [[The Wall Street Journal]] |edition=web |title=Emails Show Pentagon Official\u2019s Concerns Over Ukraine Aid Freeze |date=January 2, 2020 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/emails-show-pentagon-officials-concerns-over-ukraine-aid-freeze-11578009019 | accessdate=January 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also ==\n*[[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal]]\n*[[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump]]\n*[[Impeachment of Donald Trump]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCusker, Elaine}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Pekin, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Illinois Central College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Dallas alumni]]\n[[Category:Trump administration personnel]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Defense officials]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Elaine McCusker\n|image       = Elaine A. McCusker official photo.jpg\n|office      = Acting [[Under Secretary of Defense (Comptroller)|United States Under Secretary of Defense (Comptroller)]]\n|president   = [[Donald Trump]]\n|term_start  = July 31, 2019\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[David Norquist]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_date  = \n|birth_place = [[Pekin, Illinois]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|education   = [[Illinois Central College]]<br>[[University of Dallas]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n|awards      = [[Navy Superior Civilian Service Award]] (2008)<br>[[Secretary of Defense Exceptional Civilian Service Award]] (2011)<br>[[Department of Defense Distinguished Civilian Service Award]] (2016)\n}}\n\n'''Elaine A. McCusker''' is an American government official who has held the position of Deputy [[Under Secretary of Defense (Comptroller)]], one of the offices of [[United States Principal Deputy Under Secretary of Defense]], since 2017;<ref name=\"af-bio\">{{cite web | url = https://www.af.mil/About-Us/Biographies/Display/Article/108718/elaine-a-mccusker/ | title = Elaine A. McCusker | work = Biographies | publisher = United States Air Force | date = March 2018 | accessdate = 2019-12-30 }}</ref>  She was nominated by President [[Donald Trump]] to become United States Principal Deputy Under Secretary of Defense in April 2017 and was confirmed on August 1, 2017.<ref>{{cite news release|title=President Announces Picks for Senior Pentagon Posts|url=https://www.defense.gov/News/Article/Article/1120965/president-announces-picks-for-senior-pentagon-posts/|accessdate=May 1, 2017|publisher=United States Department of Defense}}</ref><ref>{{cite news release|title=President Donald J. Trump Announces Intent to Nominate Key Administration Posts|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/16/president-donald-j-trump-announces-intent-nominate-key-administration|accessdate=May 1, 2017|agency=Office of the Press Secretary|publisher=The White House|date=March 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kheel |first1=Rebecca|title=Navy secretary, seven other Pentagon posts confirmed|url=http://thehill.com/policy/defense/344923-navy-secretary-seven-others-confirmed |accessdate=August 4, 2017|publisher=The Hill|date=August 2, 2017}}</ref> In November 2019, the White House announced that McCusker would be nominated to succeed [[David Norquist]] as the [[Under Secretary of Defense (Comptroller)]].<ref>{{cite news release |title=President Donald J. Trump Announces Intent to Nominate Personnel to Key Administration Post |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/president-donald-j-trump-announces-intent-nominate-personnel-key-administration-post-14/ |accessdate=November 8, 2019 |website=The White House |date=November 6, 2019}}</ref> On March 2, 2020 it was reported that her nomination was being withdrawn by the White House following reports that in 2019 she had warned that freezing military aid to Ukraine might not be legal.<ref>{{cite news |title=White House withdraws nomination of Defense official who questioned Ukraine aid freeze |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/02/white-house-defense-official-nomination-118909 |first=Connor |last=O'Brien |date=March 2, 2020 |website=Politico |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>https://nypost.com/2020/03/02/trump-drops-elaine-mccuskers-pentagon-nomination-in-impeachment-fallout/</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMcCusker is from [[Pekin, Illinois]],<ref name=\"sjr-sings\"/> one of the daughters of William and Kathleen Brown McCusker. Her father was chairman of the board of the Illinois Federation for Right to Life.<ref>{{cite news | work = Pekin Daily Times | title = William McCusker | date = August 26, 2009 | url = https://www.pekintimes.com/article/20090826/NEWS/308269949 | accessdate = 2019-12-30 }}</ref> She is a graduate of [[Peoria Notre Dame High School]] and [[Illinois Central College]].<ref name=\"sjr-sings\">{{cite news | work = [[The State Journal-Register]] |edition=web |location=Springfield, Illinois | title = Pekin woman sings praises of latest combat vehicle | first=Kevin |last=Sampier | date = September 30, 2007 | url = https://www.sj-r.com/x428370762 | accessdate = 2019-12-30 }}</ref>  In 1989 she received a Bachelor of Arts in political philosophy from the [[University of Dallas]], Texas.<ref name=\"af-bio\"/>\n\n==Career==\n{{Trump-Ukraine scandal}}\nMcCusker previously worked for the [[United States Energy Department]]'s [[Argonne National Laboratory]], the [[United States Senate Committee on Armed Services]], the Pentagon Comptroller's office, and the Navy Department. At the Navy Department, she was a special assistant for the [[MRAP|Mine-Resistant Ambush Protected]] vehicle program.<ref name=\"sjr-sings\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Freedberg Jr.|first1=Sydney|last2=Clark|first2=Colin|title=Trump Picks Technocrats, Not Billionaires, For Top Pentagon Posts|url=http://breakingdefense.com/2017/03/trump-picks-technocrats-not-billionaires-for-top-pentagon-posts/|accessdate=May 1, 2017 |publisher=Breaking Defense|date=March 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMcCusker contributed to announcements in September 2019 regarding Trump's plan to divert Pentagon funds to [[Trump wall|build a wall along the U.S.-Mexico border]].  McCusker announced wall construction could begin as within three months on federally owned land. Construction of the wall on other government or privately owned land would commence at a later date, she noted.<ref>{{cite news | work = [[The Wall Street Journal]] | title = Trump Administration Advances Plan to Shift $3.6 Billion in Military Funds to Border Wall | date = September 3, 2019 | url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-administration-advances-plan-to-shift-3-6-billion-in-military-funds-to-border-wall-11567551501?mod=searchresults&page=1&pos=1 }}</ref>\n\nMcCusker has been identified as one of the federal officials with knowledge of [[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal|President Trump's effort to keep Ukraine from receiving aid authorized by Congress]]. Emails that she sent and received regarding the matter were included in documents obtained by the [[Center for Public Integrity]] in response to a [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] request.<ref>{{cite news | work = Arkansas Democrat Gazette | title = Ukraine aid frozen just after call, files show | date = December 22, 2019 | url = https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2019/dec/22/ukraine-aid-frozen-just-after-call-file/?news-national }}</ref> [[Mike Duffey|Michael Duffey]], a political appointee in White House's [[Office of Management and Budget]] (OMB), emailed McCusker and others an hour and a half after Trump\u2019s call with Ukrainian leader Zelenksy, requesting they \"hold off\" on distributing aid to the Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news | work = Vanity Fair | title = Report: White House Froze Ukraine Aid 91 Minutes After Trump Asked For a \u201cFavor\u201d | date = December 23, 2019 | first = Bess | last = Levin | url = https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/12/white-house-froze-ukraine-aid-91-minutes-after-trump-zelensky-call | accessdate = 2019-12-30 }}</ref>\n\nMcCusker then sent emails to the OMB expressing concern that by witholding funds from the Ukraine, the White House was violating the [[Congressional Budget and Impoundment Control Act of 1974|Impoundment Control Act]], which requires that the executive branch spend appropriations that have been approved by [[United States Congress|Congress]].<ref>{{cite news | work = [[The Wall Street Journal]] |edition=web |title=Emails Show Pentagon Official\u2019s Concerns Over Ukraine Aid Freeze |date=January 2, 2020 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/emails-show-pentagon-officials-concerns-over-ukraine-aid-freeze-11578009019 | accessdate=January 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also ==\n*[[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal]]\n*[[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump]]\n*[[Impeachment of Donald Trump]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCusker, Elaine}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Pekin, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Illinois Central College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Dallas alumni]]\n[[Category:Trump administration personnel]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Defense officials]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Nightscream", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:WP:DATED", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elaine_McCusker"}
{"title_page": "The New Abnormal", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = The New Abnormal\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[the Strokes]]\n| cover        = The Strokes - The New Abnormal.png\n| alt = A crude drawing of a bird \n| released     = {{startdate|2020|4|10}}\n| recorded     = 2019\n| studio       =\n* [[Shangri-La (recording studio)|Shangri-La]] ([[Malibu, California]])\n{{Collapsible list|title=Additional recording|\n* [[Studio City Sound]] ([[Studio City, Los Angeles|Studio City]], California)\n* Mauka View ([[Princeville, Hawaii]])\n* Lucy's Meat Market ([[Eagle Rock, Los Angeles|Eagle Rock]], California)\n* [[Groove Masters]] ([[Santa Monica]], California)\n* Joel and Zach's Studio ([[North Hollywood, Los Angeles|North Hollywood]], California)}}\n| genre        = <!--Please source genres-->\n* [[Indie rock]]\n* [[New wave music|new wave]]\n* [[post-punk]]\n* [[Pop music|pop]]\n* [[electronica]]\n| length       = {{duration|m=45|s=07}}\n| label        =\n* [[Cult Records|Cult]]\n* [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| producer     = [[Rick Rubin]]\n| prev_title   = [[Future Present Past]]\n| prev_year    = 2016\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = The New Abnormal\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[At the Door]]\n | single1date = February 11, 2020\n | single2     = [[Bad Decisions (The Strokes song)|Bad Decisions]]\n | single2date = February 18, 2020\n | single3     = [[Brooklyn Bridge to Chorus]]\n | single3date = April 6, 2020\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''The New Abnormal''''' is the sixth studio album by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[the Strokes]], released on April 10, 2020, through [[Cult Records|Cult]] and [[RCA Records]]. It was their first album in seven years, following ''[[Comedown Machine]]'' (2013), and their first release since the ''[[Future Present Past]]'' EP (2016).<ref name=\"PitchforkDebut\">{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-strokes-announce-new-album-debut-songs-at-bernie-sanders-rally-watch/ |title=The Strokes Announce New Album, Debut Songs at Bernie Sanders Rally: Watch |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=February 10, 2020 |accessdate=February 10, 2020 |author=Bloom, Madison}}</ref>\n\nThe album was produced by [[Rick Rubin]] and recorded at his [[Shangri-La (recording studio)|Shangri-La]] studio in [[Malibu, California]], with additional recording taking place at studios in [[Los Angeles County]] and [[Hawaii]]. The Strokes began performing songs from the album for the first time at different shows in 2019, before revealing the album's track list and cover art in early 2020. The cover art features the 1981 painting ''Bird on Money'' by American artist [[Jean-Michel Basquiat]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-strokes-tease-something-called-the-new-abnormal/ |title=The Strokes Tease Something Called The New Abnormal |last=Bloom |first=Madison |date=February 7, 2020 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |access-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''The New Abnormal'' received positive reviews from critics, with praise being directed mainly towards the maturity of the lyrics and improved cohesion among bandmates. The album was preceded by the singles \"[[At the Door]]\", \"[[Bad Decisions (The Strokes song)|Bad Decisions]]\", and \"[[Brooklyn Bridge to Chorus]]\".\n\n==Background and recording==\nWriting sessions for ''The New Abnormal'' dated as far back as 2016, following the release of the band's ''[[Future Present Past]]'' extended play from the same year. Guitarist [[Nick Valensi]] had told ''[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]]'' that they were \"slowly but surely\" making progress on the album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://diymag.com/2016/10/11/the-strokes-new-album-2017-nick-valensi-interview|title=The Strokes are \"slowly but surely working on an album\"|last=Konemann|first=Liam|date=October 11, 2016|website=DIY|publisher=|access-date=February 16, 2020}}</ref> The following year, [[Albert Hammond]], father of guitarist [[Albert Hammond Jr.]], told ''[[The West Australian]]'' that the Strokes were working with [[Rick Rubin]] on an upcoming album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewest.com.au/entertainment/music/albert-hammond-strokes-recording-with-rick-rubin-ng-b88549060z|title=Albert Hammond: Strokes recording with Rick Rubin|last=Collins|first=Simon|date=July 27, 2017|website=[[The West Australian]]|access-date=February 16, 2020}}</ref> Hammond Jr. responded to this via [[Twitter]], stating that they were only presenting musical ideas to him and were not in any recording sessions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7882102/the-strokes-not-recording-rick-rubin-album|title=The Strokes Are Not Recording With Rick Rubin After All|last=Helman|first=Peter|date=July 30, 2017|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=February 16, 2020}}</ref> The band would eventually begin recording sessions with Rubin at his [[Shangri-La (recording studio)|Shangri-La]] studio in [[Malibu, California]]. Additional recording took place at [[Studio City Sound]], Lucy's Meat Market, [[Groove Masters]], and Joel and Zach's Studio, all in [[Los Angeles County]], as well as Mauka View in [[Princeville, Hawaii]].<ref name=\"liner notes\"/>\n\nOn May 13, 2019, the band performed live for the first time in two years at the [[Wiltern Theatre]] in [[Los Angeles]], premiering a new song entitled \"The Adults Are Talking\".<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Strauss |first=Matthew |title=Watch the Strokes Perform New Song \"The Adults Are Talking\" |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-the-strokes-perform-new-song-the-adults-are-talking |magazine=[[Pitchfork (magazine)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> The show was the first of what was dubbed a \"global comeback tour\".<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Maicki |first1=Salavatore |title=The Strokes are planning a \"global comeback\" tour for 2019 |url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/12/18/the-strokes-2019-comeback-tour-bilbao |magazine=[[The Fader]] |accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref> Early shows were plagued by technical difficulties ranging from sound issues<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Connor |first1=Roisin |title=All Points East: The Strokes gig compared to 'underwater karaoke' by fans annoyed over sound issues |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/the-strokes-all-points-east-gig-sound-quality-issues-fans-complaints-a8930761.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> to rain-outs<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Aswad |first1=Jem |last2=Sabla |first2=Elvin |title=Governors Ball Festival Evacuated Due to Thunderstorms, Multiple Acts Cancelled |url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/governors-ball-evacuated-festival-thunderstorm-cancelled-1203231235/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> to cancellations of entire festivals.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Cantor-Navas |first1=Judy |title=Doctor Music Festival Canceled After Move From Mountain Pastures to Barcelona Racetrack |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/festivals/8515958/doctor-music-festival-canceled-barcelona |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\nMusic critics have generally considered ''The New Abnormal'' to be an [[indie rock]] album.<ref name=\"Chicago\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-ent-the-strokes-the-new-abnormal-review-20200408-ugjwag6x2fa3xfq7vx7ierpbn4-story.html |title=Review: The Strokes triumph on their 1st album in 7 years |last=Kennedy |first=Mark |date=April 8, 2020 |website=[[Chicago Tribune]] |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=themusic>{{Cite web |url=https://themusic.com.au/reviews/the-strokes-the-new-abnormal-anna-rose/KL8wOj08Pz4/09-04-20/ |title=The Strokes / The New Abnormal |last=Rose |first=Anna |date=April 9, 2020 |website=[[The Music (magazine)|The Music]] |access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gigwise\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.gigwise.com/reviews/3376046/album-review-the-strokes-the-new-abnormal |title=Album Review: The Strokes - The New Abnormal |last=Pywell |first=Matty |date=April 6, 2020 |website=[[Gigwise]] |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Matty Pywell of ''[[Gigwise]]'' wrote that it blended indie rock and \"[[New wave music|new wave]] mixed with [[electronica]]\".<ref name=\"Gigwise\"/> Writing for ''[[Newsweek]]'', James Crowley wrote that the album sonically leans more towards the \"[[disco]]-tinged [[post-punk]] than the [[Garage rock revival|garage rock]] they made their name with,\"<ref name=\"Newsweek\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/strokes-hamilton-leithauser-sparta-tory-lanez-new-albums-1497136 |title=The Strokes, Hamilton Leithauser and more release new music: what you should listen to today |last=Crowley |first=James |date=April 10, 2020 |website=[[Newsweek]] |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> while [[Kitty Empire]] of ''[[The Observer]]'' labeled it as \"all-out pop\".<ref name=\"The Observer\"/> Writers have also considered the album as having elements of [[1980s in music|1980s]] [[pop music]],<ref name=\"cos\"/><ref name=themusic/> [[glam rock]],<ref name=\"Chicago\"/> and [[dream pop]].<ref name=\"Chicago\"/> Two songs on the album incorporate vocal melodies from other songs into them, both of which include songwriting credits for the original performers.<ref name=\"liner notes\"/> The chorus of \"[[Bad Decisions (The Strokes song)|Bad Decisions]]\" uses the vocal melody from the chorus of \"[[Dancing with Myself]]\" (1980) by [[Generation X (band)|Generation X]],<ref name=\"Chicago\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newcastleherald.com.au/story/6721354/the-strokes-settle-into-abnormal-middle-age-on-comeback/ |title=Review: The Strokes - The New Abnormal - 3 stars |last=Leeson |first=Josh |date=April 13, 2020 |website=[[The Newcastle Herald]] |access-date=April 14, 2020}}</ref> and some of \"Eternal Summer\" uses the vocal melody from the chorus of \"[[The Ghost in You]]\" (1984) by [[the Psychedelic Furs]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-new-abnormal-review-not-so-different-strokes-11586380894 |title='The New Abnormal' Review: Not-So-Different Strokes |last=Richardson |first=Mark |date=April 8, 2020 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |access-date=April 13, 2020 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion==\nTo compensate for the cancellation of their performance at the [[Governors Ball Music Festival]] on June 2, 2019, the band played a special [[New Year's Eve]] show at [[Barclays Center]] in [[Brooklyn]] with [[Mac DeMarco]], [[Kirin J Callinan]] and [[Hinds (band)|Hinds]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Daramola |first1=Israel |title=The Strokes Announce New Year's Eve Show in Brooklyn |url=https://www.spin.com/2019/08/the-strokes-new-years-eve-show-brooklyn/ |magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> During the show, Casablancas announced the release of a new album, stating, \"Yeah, we\u2019ve got a new album coming out soon ... The 2010s, whatever the fuck they\u2019re called, we took \u2018em off. And now we\u2019ve been unfrozen and we\u2019re back.\" The band also premiered another new song entitled \"Ode to the [[New York Mets|Mets]]\".<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Arcand |first1=Rob |title=The Strokes Play New Song \"Ode To The Mets,\" Say New Album Is Coming in 2020 at Brooklyn NYE Performance |url=https://www.spin.com/2020/01/the-strokes-ode-to-the-mets-new-album-coming-in-2020-brooklyn-nye-performance/ |magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> Other notable performances included a rally for [[Bernie Sanders]] in [[Durham, New Hampshire]] on February 10, 2020, alongside [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]], [[Sunflower Bean]], [[Cynthia Nixon]], and [[Cornel West]].<ref name=\"Bernie\">{{cite magazine |last1=Bloom |first1=Madison |title=The Strokes Debut New Song \"Bad Decision\" at Bernie Sanders Rally: Watch |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-strokes-announce-new-album-debut-songs-at-bernie-sanders-rally-watch/ |magazine=[[Pitchfork (magazine)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> There, Casablancas confirmed that the new album, titled ''The New Abnormal'', would be released on April 10, while the band debuted one new song, \"Bad Decisions\", and screened a music video for another, \"At the Door\".<ref name=\"Bernie\"/>\n\nTo further promote the record, the band released a series of self-produced videos titled and stylized as \"5guys talking about things they know nothing about.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/04/the-strokes-pirate-radio-show/|title=The Strokes launch pirate radio show|date=2020-04-09|website=Consequence of Sound|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The band explained that \"...we wanted to see if we could connect with folks, and turned what was supposed to be a pirate radio thing for our album release (which we would make in-person) into a video chat instead...\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-vXVuyFvw_/|title=Albert Hammond Jr\u2019s Instagram post: \u201cUP & RUNNING!\u2063 \u2063 Hello prisoners of earth,\u2063 \u2063 Like many out there we are staying pretty much at home and keeping to ourselves. We wanted to\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The first episode premiered on April 8, 2020, and in the following episode, released April 9, 2020, the band previewed the entire record.<ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_New_Abnormal?veaction=edit&section=2|title=The Strokes - 5guys talking about things they know nothing about - Episode 2|date=April 9, 2020|last=The Strokes|first=|type=video|language=}}</ref> \n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 76/100<ref name=\"MC\"/>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score ={{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-new-abnormal-mw0003357997 |title=The New Abnormal - The Strokes {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits |last=Phares |first=Heather |date=April 10, 2020 |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev2score = B<ref name=\"cos\">{{cite web|author=Tyler Clark |url= https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/04/album-review-the-strokes-the-new-abnormal/ |title= The Strokes Reignite on The New Abnormal|website=Consequence of Sound|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3score = A\u2013<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/music/music-reviews/the-strokes-review/ |title=The Strokes return, unbound, on The New Abnormal |last=Greenblatt  |first=Leah |date=April 6, 2020 |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev4score = 6/10<ref name=\"Exclaim\">{{Cite web |url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/the_strokes_new_abnormal_review |title=The Strokes: The New Abnormal |last=Bell |first=Kaelen |date=April 10, 2020 |website=[[Exclaim!]] |access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/10/the-strokes-the-new-abnormal-review |title=The Strokes: The New Abnormal review \u2013 old magic lights fresh sparks |last=Aroesti |first=Rachel |website=[[The Guardian]] |date=April 10, 2020 |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev6score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/the-strokes-review-new-abnormal-tracklist-stream-julian-casablancas-a9453296.html |title=The Strokes review, The New Abnormal: Charged with a tense ennui fit for the present lockdown |last=Brown |first=Helen |website=[[The Independent]] |date=April 8, 2020 |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev7score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/the-strokes-the-new-abnormal-review-2640779 |title=The Strokes \u2013 \u2018The New Abnormal\u2019 review: proof that they\u2019re still the best riff-makers around |last=Kemp |first=Ella |website=[[NME]] |date=April 6, 2020 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev8score = 5.7/10<ref name=\"p4k\">{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/the-strokes-the-new-abnormal/ |title=The Strokes - The New Abnormal |last=Sodomsky |first=Sam |date=April 10, 2020 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev9score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/the-strokes-the-new-abnormal-981609/ |title=The Strokes Heart the Eighties and Sound Like Themselves on 'The New Abnormal' |last=Dolan |first=Jon |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=April 10, 2020 |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Times]]''\n| rev10score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"The Times\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-strokes-the-new-abnormal-review-this-makes-the-new-york-band-fascinating-and-vital-again-plpdkdp5b/ |title=The Strokes: The New Abnormal review \u2014 this makes the New York band fascinating and vital again\u2019 |last=Hodgkinson |first=Will |website=[[The Times]] |date=April 10, 2020 |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nMedia response to ''The New Abnormal'' has been positive. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received a weighted average score of 76, based on 21 reviews, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref name=\"MC\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/the-new-abnormal/the-strokes/critic-reviews |title=Critic Reviews for The New Abnormal by The Strokes |website=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> Most critics praised the maturity in lyricism as well as the bandmates' return to form in terms of cohesion. The latter, in regards to the tension and apathy from within the group, was a talking point for much of the last decade.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gq.com/story/the-strokes-retrospective |title=The Fifteen-Year Decline of the Strokes |last=Nguyen |first=Kevin |website=[[GQ]] |date=August 12, 2016 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the album an A-, acknowledging that \"twenty years on from the band's first flush of stardom, ''Abnormal'' offers something better than reckless youth: rock stars finally old enough to miss those good old days\u2014and wise enough now, too, to give us the soundtrack these strange new times deserve.\"<ref name=\"EW\"/> ''[[NME]]'' awarded the album four stars, with Ella Kemp remarking, \"The Strokes have always kept their feelings at arm\u2019s length, but there are traces of deeper introspection on their sixth album, which\u2014despite itself\u2014is something of a crowd-pleaser.\"<ref name=\"NME\"/>\n\nIn the review for [[AllMusic]], Heather Phares praised the album, claiming it to be \"Full of passion, commitment, and creativity\" and that \"The New Abnormal marks the first time in a while that the Strokes have made truly exciting music.\"<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> Giving the verdict for ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'', Tyler Clark stated that \"Even with its inevitable blemishes, The New Abnormal is easily the freshest, most interesting album that The Strokes have released in more than a decade. While the band haven\u2019t proven to be the single-handed savior that rock music always seems to be searching for, they have made the case for taking a slow-burn approach to collaboration and creativity. In that respect, this album might just be the first step along a new, more invigorated path.\"<ref name=\"cos\"/>  Rachel Aroesti also provided a positive assessment in the review for ''[[the Guardian]]'', writing that \"when they put their minds to it, that old magic is still well within the Strokes\u2019s grasp.\"<ref name=\"The Guardian\"/>\n\nSome reviewers were more critical in their judgement of the album. In the review for ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'', Sam Sodomsky mentioned that \"the Strokes' sixth album and first in seven years, mostly just feels like a hangover. It's sluggish and slight, and the strongest hooks are so familiar that they require additional writing credits for the '80s hits they copy note-for-note\"<ref name=\"p4k\"/> [[Neil McCormick]] of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' gave the album three stars out of five, criticzing its \"cheesy Eighties synths and dinky disco beats\" as well as Julian Casablancas' lyrics, but praised its instrumentation and Casablancas's vocals, as well as Rick Rubin's production for making The Strokes sound \"pretty damn fantastic again.\"<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/weeks-best-new-albums-laura-marling-strokes-chimpan/ |title=This week's best new albums: Laura Marling, The Strokes, Chimpan A |last=McCormick |first=Neil |authorlink=Neil McCormick |date=April 9, 2020 |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Reviewing the album for ''[[Exclaim!]]'', Kaelen Bell had mixed feelings, saying that it is \"not a bad record, but it is a frustrating one, made by a band that feels pulled in a dozen different directions.\"<ref name=\"Exclaim\"/> [[Kitty Empire]] of ''[[the Observer]]'' also regarded the album as a \"frustrating listen despite its gleam\", adding that \"faster tempos would have helped.\"<ref name=\"The Observer\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/11/the-strokes-the-new-abnormal-review-new-found-focus |title=The Strokes: The New Abnormal review \u2013 new found focus |last=Empire |first=Kitty |authorlink=Kitty Empire |website=[[The Observer]] |date=April 11, 2020 |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll lyrics are written by [[Julian Casablancas]]; all music is composed by the Strokes, except where noted.<ref name=\"liner notes\">{{cite AV media notes|title=The New Abnormal|others=[[The Strokes]]|year=2020|type=vinyl sleeve|publisher=[[Cult Records]]; [[RCA Records]]|id=19439-70588-1}}</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| total_length = 45:07\n| title1 = The Adults Are Talking\n| length1 = 5:09\n| title2 = Selfless\n| length2 = 3:42\n| title3 = [[Brooklyn Bridge to Chorus]]\n| length3 = 3:55\n| title4 = [[Bad Decisions (The Strokes song)|Bad Decisions]]\n| length4 = 4:53\n| note4  = The Strokes, [[Billy Idol]], [[Tony James (musician)|Tony James]]\n| title5 = Eternal Summer\n| length5 = 6:15\n| note5  = The Strokes, [[Richard Butler (singer)|Richard Lofthouse Butler]], [[Tim Butler|Timothy Butler]]<!-- These are the names they are credited with in the liner notes -->\n| title6 = [[At the Door]]\n| length6 = 5:10\n| note6  = The Strokes, Paul Vassallo\n| title7 = Why Are Sundays So Depressing\n| length7 = 4:35\n| title8 = Not the Same Anymore\n| length8 = 5:37\n| title9 = Ode to the Mets\n| length9 = 5:51\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from the album's liner notes.<ref name=\"liner notes\"/>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Engineers'''\n* [[Jason Lader]] \u2013\u00a0engineering, mixing {{small|(tracks 4\u20137, 9)}}\n* Pete Min \u2013\u00a0additional engineering\n* Rob Bisel \u2013\u00a0assistant engineering\n* Dylan Neustadter \u2013\u00a0assistant engineering\n* Kevin Smith \u2013\u00a0assistant engineering\n* Gus Oberg \u2013\u00a0pre-production demo recordings and engineering\n* Chris Tabron \u2013\u00a0additional pre-production demo recordings and engineering\n* Ben Baptie \u2013\u00a0mixing {{small|(tracks 1\u20133, 8)}}\n* Stephen Marcussen \u2013 mastering\n* Stewart Whitmore \u2013\u00a0mastering\n{{col-2}}\n'''The Strokes'''\n* [[Julian Casablancas]] \u2013 vocals\n* [[Albert Hammond Jr.]] \u2013\u00a0guitar\n* [[Nick Valensi]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Nikolai Fraiture]] \u2013\u00a0bass\n* [[Fabrizio Moretti]] \u2013\u00a0drums\n\n'''Artwork'''\n* [[Jean-Michel Basquiat]] \u2013\u00a0cover painting (''Bird on Money'', 1981)\n* Tina Iba\u00f1ez \u2013 [[art direction]], design\n* Jason McDonald \u2013\u00a0photography\n{{col-end}}\n\n<!-- Please DO NOT remove this. For editor's reference. Will fill in when charts are published.\t\n==Charts==\t\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|\u2212\t\n!Chart (2020)\n!Peak<br /> position\t\n!Weeks on chart\t\n|-\n\u2212\t\n| [[ARIA Charts|Australian Albums]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=The+Strokes&titel=The+New+Abnormal&cat=a |title=The Strokes - The New Abnormal |date=April 15, 2020 |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|#\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|#\n|-\n| [[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|Austrian Albums]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|#\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|#\n|-\n| [[Ultratop|Belgian Albums (Ultratop) Flanders)]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/album/61fec/The-Strokes-The-New-Abnormal |title=The Strokes - The New Abnormal |publisher=[[Ultratop]] |date=April 13, 2020 |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|#\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|#\n|-\n| [[Ultratop|Belgian Albums (Ultratop) Wallonia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/fr/album/61fec/The-Strokes-The-New-Abnormal |title=The Strokes - The New Abnormal |publisher=[[Ultratop]] |date=April 13, 2020 |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|#\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|#\n|-\n| [[Canadian Albums Chart|Canadian Albums]] ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/The-Strokes/chart-history/CNA |title=The Strokes - The New Abnormal |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=April 13, 2020 |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|#\